<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Lemma"
         id="Thm_IsomorphismInvertible"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle2.5/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Isomorphism same as invertible</caption>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>A linear transformation <math>
               <latex>L\from V\to W</latex>
            </math> is an isomorphism if and only if it is an invertible linear map.</para.body>
      </para>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof type="Proof">
      <proof.block>
         <para>
            <para.body>We consider first the case where <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> is an isomorphism. We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> is an invertible linear map. We begin by showing that <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> is an invertible function: Indeed, <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> is onto because it is epimorphic. To see that it is one-to-one, let <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
               </math> be in <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> with <math>
                  <latex>L(\Vect{x}) = L(\Vect{y})</latex>
               </math>. Then</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{0} = L(\Vect{x}) - L(\Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>L(\Vect{x} - \Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>Therefore <math>
                  <latex>(\Vect{x} - \Vect{y})</latex>
               </math> is in <math>
                  <latex>\ker(L) = \Set{ \Vect{0} }</latex>
               </math>, implying that</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>Therefore <math>
                  <latex>(\Vect{x} - \Vect{y})</latex>
               </math> is in <math>
                  <latex>\ker(L) = \Vect{0}</latex>
               </math> and so <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x} = \Vect{y}</latex>
               </math>.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>Therefore <math>
                  <latex>L\from V\to W</latex>
               </math> is an invertible function. It remains to show:</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>
               <math>
                  <latex>L^{-1} \from W \to V</latex>
               </math> is linear. So let <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}_1</latex>
               </math>, <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}_2</latex>
               </math> be in <math>
                  <latex>W</latex>
               </math>, and let <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}_1</latex>
               </math>, <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}_2</latex>
               </math> be the unique vectors in <math>
                  <latex>V</latex>
               </math> with <math>
                  <latex>L(\Vect{x}_1) = \Vect{y}_1</latex>
               </math> and <math>
                  <latex>L(\Vect{x}_2) = \Vect{y}_2</latex>
               </math>, respectively. Then we see that <math>
                  <latex>L^{-1}</latex>
               </math> commutes with vector addition by computing:</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>L^{-1}(\Vect{y}_1 + \Vect{y}_2)</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>L^{-1}(L(\Vect{x}_1) + L(\Vect{x}_2))</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>L^{-1}(L(\Vect{x}_1+\Vect{x}_2))</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}_1 + \Vect{x}_2</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>L^{-1}(\Vect{y}_1) + L^{-1}(\Vect{y}_2)</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>So <math>
                  <latex>L^{-1}</latex>
               </math> commutes with vector addition. To see that it commutes with scalar multiplication as well, let <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y} = L(\Vect{x})</latex>
               </math> be in <math>
                  <latex>W</latex>
               </math>, and let <math>
                  <latex>t</latex>
               </math> be in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr</latex>
               </math>. Then we find:</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>L^{-1}(t\cdot \Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>L^{-1}(t\cdot L(\Vect{x}))</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>L^{-1}(L(t\cdot \Vect{x}))</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t\cdot \Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex/>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>t\cdot L^{-1}(\Vect{y})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>Thus <math>
                  <latex>L^{-1}</latex>
               </math> commutes with scalar multiplication as well. This completes the proof that an isomorphism is an invertible linear map.</para.body>
         </para>
         <para>
            <para.body>Consider next the case where <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> is an invertible linear map. So we know that <math>
                  <latex>L^{-1}</latex>
               </math> exists and is linear. We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> is an isomorphism.  To see that <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> is monomorphic, suppose <math>
                  <latex>L(\Vect{x}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
               </math>  for some <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x}\in V</latex>
               </math>. We need to show that <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{x} = \Vect{0}</latex>
               </math>. Indeed, we have</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x} = L^{-1}(L(\Vect{x}))</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>L^{-1}(\Vect{0})</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle"/>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=	</latex>
                  </math>
                  <companion>
                     <info>
                        <info.caption>Why is this so?</info.caption>
                        <para>
                           <para.body>Recall that a linear map <math>
                                 <latex>T</latex>
                              </math> always satisfies <math>
                                 <latex>T(\Vect{0}) = \Vect{0}</latex>
                              </math>.</para.body>
                        </para>
                     </info>
                  </companion>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{0}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>Next we show that <math>
                  <latex>L</latex>
               </math> is epimorphic. Indeed, if <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y} \in W</latex>
               </math> is arbitrary, we have</para.body>
         </para>
         <math.array column="3">
            <row rowspan="1">
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>=</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
               <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                  <math>
                     <latex>L(L^{-1}(\Vect{y}))</latex>
                  </math>
               </cell>
            </row>
         </math.array>
         <para>
            <para.body>and, therefore, <math>
                  <latex>\Vect{y}</latex>
               </math> is in <math>
                  <latex>\im(L)</latex>
               </math>. - This completes the proof of the lemma.</para.body>
         </para>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
